review_blob: Outstanding! Beautiful near black pour, opaque even held up to the light, smooth tan head. Subtle nose- roasty malt with just a hint of coffee. Thin (for a stout) and slightly oily in the mouth. Flavor dry, terrifically balanced dark roast and the coffee is not at all astringent, but smooth and creamy and reinforcing the low dark notes of roast malts.
Very nice. More iipa than tripel. Hazey honey pour with stiff off-white head.  Smells of grapefruit and pine with spice notes. More of the same in the taste, very forward hops

Bottle. Very Stone, but doing what they do well-- big hoppy high alcohol beer. Not very remarkable, but enjoyable. Pours a deep tobacco red brown, nose is spruce and malt, with alcohol evident. Lingering tan foam, taste is warm grapefuit and pine followed by toffee malt, lingering bitter.
Kinda ordinary. Not bad at all, but nothing super memorable. a bit more dark malt than usual. Has anyone graphed the last decade in indepents/beer brands?

Yuck. Dunno if this was an off keg or just not my taste. Syrupy, with a greasy skim of a head. I get the hazelnut thing, but to me this was flat, tasted lIke old coffee and old sugar. Not for me, I guess. Disgusting. But only a lot. Stale keg?

Draft at Deep Ellum. Slightly hazy straw, fine sticky head. Aroma is IPA with a hint of something else behind the hops. Fruit, with a touch of leather and must. Tastes like IPA at first, hops up front with spruce and flowers, as that fades a pleasant belgian blend of banana and earth. Really nice. Have a bottle at home Im looking forward to as well.

Draft at Deep Ellum. A giant IPA start to finish. Everything is amped up-- hops, maltiness, body-- but kept in balance. Alcohol is noticeable, but along with the bitterness and carbonation opposes the high gravity. Dont know that Id call it "quaffable" but certainly enjoyable.
Black, viscous pour, aroma of fruit and dark roasty goodness. Heavy in the mouth, almost a stout but still not as chewy, with sour fruit and a lasting tang.

Pleasant, if mild, gueuze. Good introduction to the style, Id say, though not the place to look if youre seeking something funky. Straw colored pour, smells of citrus and bread, lively carbonation and quite fruity acid, Refreshing and enjoyable (from a nice fresh keg) but not especially memorable
Pours maple syrup brown with durable head, aroma is hops and hot metal. Mouth is heavy, hint of alcohol, nicely fizzed carbonation. Taste is grapefruit and coffee syrup. Lasting bitter finish.

Pretty orange amber pour, thick fluffy lingering head, hops galore in the aroma, bit on the syrupy side for me but powerful hops at the front with a smooth malt and lots of lingering pungent tang. Hoppy-licious.

Fantastic. Pours brown with hints of red, nice large grained head, strong nose spruce and spice, taste has the dry spice of the rye up front, lingering hops. Big mouth feel, with some heat. Really liked this bottle. Have never enjoyed it quite so much on draft.
beer_name: Bear Republic Hop Rod Rye Ale

review_blob: Draft at Deep Ellum, then bottle at home. Just outstanding. Red orange with small persistent head. Aroma bready but balanced with citrus and spice. Big in the mouth but not too sweet, belgian yeast and malt opposed by light hop bitterness and a hint of sour.

Nice amber pour, nose of caramel and pine resin-- fresh hops. Sweetness and body as you would expect greater than an IPA but well balanced by hops and carbonation. None of the cloying syrupy quality of many brown/amber ales. Goes down deceptively easily for a 6% beer.
